    {
      "section": "AI \u2014 News & Analysis",
      "source": "Simon Willison",
      "title": "sqlite-utils 4.1",
      "url": "https://simonwillison.net/2026/Jul/11/sqlite-utils/#atom-everything",
      "published": "2026-07-11T23:50:20+00:00",
      "summary": "Release: sqlite-utils 4.1\n        The first dot-release since 4.0 a few days ago, introducing a number of minor new features.\n\n\nsqlite-utils insert and sqlite-utils upsert now accept a --code option for providing a block of Python code (or a path to a .py file) that defines a rows() function or rows iterable of rows to insert, as an alternative to importing from a file. (#684)\n\n\nsqlite-utils already had features that allow you to pass blocks of Python code as CLI arguments, for example this one for the sqlite-utils convert command:\nsqlite-utils convert content.db articles headline '\ndef conver"
    }
  ]
